'''Islay''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=islay.ogg|<U+02C8>|a<U+026A>|l|<U+0259>}} {{respell|EYE|l<U+0259>}}; {{lang-gd|<U+00CC>le}}, {{IPA-gd|<U+02C8>i<U+02D0>l<U+0259>|pron}}), is the southernmost island of the [[Inner Hebrides]] of Scotland. Known as "The Queen of the Hebrides",<ref name=Newton11>Newton (1995) p. 11</ref> it lies in [[Argyll]] just south west of [[Jura, Scotland|Jura]] and around {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of the Irish coast. The island's capital and largest settlement is [[Bowmore]] where the distinctive round [[Kilarrow Parish Church]] and a distillery are located.<ref name=GRO08/><ref name=Newton20>Newton (1995) p. 20</ref> [[Port Ellen]] is the main port.<ref>Newton (1995) p. 31</ref>

Islay is the fifth largest Scottish island and the seventh largest [[List of islands of the British Isles|island surrounding Great Britain]], with a total area of almost {{convert|620|km2|sqmi|0}}.{{#tag:ref|Haswell-Smith (2004) has a table of Scottish "islands arranged in order of magnitude" that lists Islay as fifth in rank, although this excludes [[Skye]] as it is a bridged island and includes [[South Uist]] as fourth on the grounds that it is connected to other islands such as [[Benbecula]] and [[North Uist]] by causeways that give it a large area.<ref>Haswell-Smith (2004) p. 502</ref> Rick Livingstone<U+2019>s Tables provide all the relevant area data although the information is not ranked.<ref name=Rick>[http://www.argyll-yachtcharters.co.uk/Scottish%20Islands.pdf Rick Livingstone<U+2019>s Tables of the Islands of Scotland] (pdf) Argyll Yacht Charters. Retrieved 12 Dec 2011.</ref> [[Ireland]] is the largest of the islands surrounding Great Britain and [[Anglesey]] the sixth largest.|group="Note"}} There is ample evidence of the prehistoric settlement of Islay and the first written reference may have come in the 1st century AD.  The island had become part of the Gaelic Kingdom of [[D<U+00E1>l Riata]] during the [[Scotland in the Early Middle Ages|Early Middle Ages]] before being absorbed into the Norse [[Kingdom of the Isles]]. The later [[medieval]] period marked a "cultural high point" with the transfer of the [[Hebrides]] to the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] and the emergence of the [[Clan Donald]] [[Lord of the Isles|Lordship of the Isles]], originally centred at [[Finlaggan]].<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 58</ref> During the 17th century the Clan Donald star waned, but improvements to agriculture and transport led to a rising population, which peaked in the mid-19th century.<ref name="HSmith41"/> This was followed by substantial [[Highland Clearances|forced displacements]] and declining resident numbers. 

Today, it has over three thousand inhabitants and the main commercial activities are agriculture, [[Islay whisky|malt whisky distillation]] and tourism. The island has a long history of religious observance and [[Scottish Gaelic]] is spoken by about a quarter of the population.<ref name=MacT>Mac an T<U+00E0>illeir, Iain (2004) [http://www.linguae-celticae.org/dateien/Gaelic_1901-2001.ppt  ''1901-2001 Gaelic in the Census''] (PowerPoint) Linguae Celticae. Retrieved 19 September 2012.</ref> Its landscapes have been celebrated through various art forms and there is a growing interest in [[Renewable energy in Scotland|renewable energy]]. Islay is home to many bird species such as the wintering populations of [[Greater White-fronted Goose|Greenland White-fronted]] and [[Barnacle Goose]], and is a popular destination throughout the year for birdwatchers. The climate is mild and ameliorated by the [[Gulf Stream]].

==Geography==
[[File:Islay topographic map-en.svg|thumb|Topographic map]]
Islay is {{convert|40|km|mi}} long from north to south and some {{convert|24|km|mi}} broad. The east coast is rugged and mountainous, rising steeply from the [[Sound of Islay]], the highest peak being [[Beinn Bheigier]], which is a [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]] at 1,612 feet (491 m). The western peninsulas are separated from the main bulk of the island by the waters of [[Loch Indaal]] to the south and [[Loch Gruinart]] to the north.<ref>Murray (1966) pp. 22<U+2013>23</ref> The fertile and windswept south western arm is called [[Rinns of Islay|The Rinns]], and [[Ardnave Point]] is a conspicuous promontory on the northwest coast.  The south coast is sheltered from the prevailing winds and, as a result, relatively wooded.<ref>Murray (1966) p. 32</ref><ref>Newton (1995) p. 42</ref><ref name=OS/> The [[fractal]] coast has numerous bays  and sea lochs, including [[Loch an t-Sailein]], [[Aros Bay]] and [[Claggain Bay]].<ref name=OS/> In the far south-west is a rocky and now largely uninhabited peninsula called [[The Oa]], the closest point in the Hebrides to [[Ireland]].<ref>Murray (1966) p. 30</ref>

The island's population is mainly centred around the villages of [[Bowmore]] and [[Port Ellen]]. Other smaller villages include [[Bridgend, Islay|Bridgend]], [[Ballygrant]], [[Port Charlotte, Islay|Port Charlotte]], [[Portnahaven]] and [[Port Askaig]]. The rest of the island is sparsely populated and mainly agricultural.<ref name=Caldwellxxv>Caldwell (2011) p. xxv</ref> There are several small freshwater [[loch]]s in the interior including [[Finlaggan|Loch Finlaggan]], Loch Ballygrant, Loch Lossit and Loch Gorm and numerous [[Stream|burns]] throughout the island, many of which bear the name "river" despite their small size. The most significant of these are the [[River Laggan, Islay|River Laggan]] which discharges into the sea at the north end of Laggan Bay and the [[River Sorn]] which, draining Loch Finlaggan, enters the head of Loch Indaal at Bridgend.<ref name=OS/>

There are numerous small uninhabited islands around the coasts, the largest of which are [[Eilean Mhic Coinnich]] and [[Orsay, Inner Hebrides|Orsay]] off the Rinns, [[Nave Island]] on the north west coast, [[Claig Castle|Am Fraoch Eilean]] in the Sound of Islay and [[Texa]] off the south coast.<ref name=OS/>

===Geology and geomorphology===
[[File:Islay Geology.png|left|Geological map of Islay|thumb]]
The underlying geology of Islay is intricate for such a small area.<ref name=HSmith41/> The deformed [[Palaeoproterozoic]] [[igneous rock]] of the [[Rhinns complex]] is dominated by a course-grained [[gneiss]] cut by large intrusions of  deformed [[gabbro]]. Once thought to be part of the [[Lewisian complex]], it lies beneath the [[Colonsay Group]] of [[Metasediment|metasedimentary rocks]]<ref name="Daly_1991">{{cite journal|last=Daly|first=J.S.|coauthors=Muir R.J. & Cliff R.A.|date=1991|title=A precise U-Pb zircon age for the Inishtrahull syenitic gneiss, County Donegal, Ireland|journal=Journal of the Geological Society|publisher=[[Geological Society]]|volume=148|pages=639<U+2013>642|url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/content/148/4/639.short|accessdate=15 September 2012|doi=10.1144/gsjgs.148.4.0639|issue=4}}</ref><ref name="Muir_1994">{{cite book|last=Muir|first=R.J.|coauthors=Fitches W.R., Maltman A.J. & Bentley M.R.|title=A Revised Correlation of Precambrian Rocks in the British Isles|editor=Harris A.L. & Gibbons W.|publisher=[[Geological Society]]|location=London|date=1994|edition=2|series=Special Report|volume=22|pages=54<U+2013>56|chapter=Precambrian rocks of the southern Inner Hebrides<U+2014>Malin Sea region: Colonsay, west Islay, Inishtrahull and Iona|isbn=9781897799116|url=http://books.google.com/?id=e07_AvEChXMC&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=inishtrahull+Precambrian+Colonsay+Iona+Muir#v=onepage&q=inishtrahull%20Precambrian%20Colonsay%20Iona%20Muir&f=false|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> which forms the bedrock at the northern end of the Rinns. It is a [[quartz]]-rich [[metamorphic rock|metamorphic]] marine sandstone that may be unique to Scotland and which is nearly 5,000 metres thick.<ref>Gillen (2003) p. 65</ref> South of Rubh' a' Mhail there are outcrops of [[quartzite]], and a strip of [[mica schist]] and [[limestone]] cuts across the centre of the island from The Oa to Port Askaig. Further south is a band of metamorphic quartzite and granites, a continuation of the beds that underlie Jura. The [[geomorphology]] of these last two zones is dominated by a [[Fold (geology)|fold]] known as the Islay Anticline. To the south is a "shattered coastline" formed from mica schist and [[hornblende]].<ref name=HSmith41/><ref>Haswell-Smith (2004) p. 47</ref><ref name=NatHist>[http://www.islaynaturalhistory.org/geology/geology.htm "Islay Geology"]. Islay Natural History Trust. Retrieved 18 Sept 2012.</ref> The older Bowmore Group sandstones in the west-centre of the island are rich in [[feldspar]] and may be of [[Dalradian]] origin.<ref>Strachan, R. A, Smith, M., Harris, A. L., Fettes, D. J. "The Northern Highland and Grampian Terranes" in Trewin (2002) p. 96</ref>{{#tag:ref|The Rhinns complex, named after the Islay peninsula which hosts its largest outcrop, is predominantly [[Palaeoproterozoic]] [[syenite|syenitic]] gneiss. It lies [[Unconformity|unconformably]] beneath the Colonsay Group.<ref name="Daly_1991"/>|group="Note"}}
[[File:Rocks near Claddach bay - geograph.org.uk - 565909.jpg|thumb|Rocks of the [[Rhinns complex]] at Claddach Bay on the southernmost tip of the [[Rinns of Islay|Rinns]]]]
Loch Indaal was formed along a branch of the [[Great Glen Fault]] called the Loch Gruinart Fault; its main line passes just to the north of [[Colonsay]]. This separates the limestone, igneous intrusions and Bowmore sandstones from the Colonsay Group rocks of the Rhinns.<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://eprints.gla.ac.uk/225/01/Thomas%5B1%5D.pdf| title=Sr chemostratigraphy of Neoproterozoic Dalradian limestones of Scotland and Ireland: constraints on depositional ages and time scales|author=Thomas, Christopher W.; Graham, Colin M.; Ellam, Robert M.; & Fallick, Anthony E| publisher=Journal of the Geological Society|volume=161|pages=229<U+2013>242|format=pdf| accessdate=22 Mar 2012}}</ref> The result is occasional minor earth tremors.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.earthquakes.bgs.ac.uk/macroseismics/jura_macro.htm| title=Jura Earthquake 3 May 1998| publisher=[[British Geological Survey]]| accessdate=23 Jan 2008}}</ref>

There is a [[tillite]] bed near Port Askaig that provides evidence of an [[ice age]] in the [[Pre-Cambrian]].<ref>Keay and Keay (1994) p. 547</ref><ref name=NatHist/> In comparatively recent times the island was ice-covered during the [[Pleistocene]] glaciations save for Beinn Tart a' Mhill on the Rinns, which was a [[nunatak]] on the edge of the ice sheet.<ref>Mithen (2006) p. 197</ref> The complex changes of sea level due to melting ice caps and [[isostasy]] since then have left a series of raised beaches around the coast.<ref name=Caldwellxxv/> Throughout much of late prehistory the low-lying land between the Rinns and the rest of the island was flooded, creating two islands.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 4</ref>

===Climate===
The influence of the [[Gulf Stream]] keeps the climate mild compared to mainland Scotland. Snow is rarely seen at sea level and frosts are light and short-lived.<ref name=Met>[http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/regmapavge.html#wscotland "Regional mapped climate averages: W Scotland"]. Met office. Retrieved 22 Mar 2012.</ref> However, wind speeds average {{convert|19 |to|28|km/h|kn}} annually<ref>[http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/ukmapavge.html "UK mapped climate averages"]. Met office. Retrieved 16 Sept 2012.</ref> and winter gales sweep in off the [[Atlantic]], gusting up to {{convert|185|kph|mph}}.<ref>[http://www.islayjura.com/?page_id=113 "Weather"]. Islayjura.com. Retrieved 16 Sept 2012.</ref> This can make travelling and living on the island during the winter difficult,<ref>Newton (1995) p. 9</ref> while ferry and air links to the mainland can suffer delays.  The driest months are April to July and the warmest are May to September, which as a result are the busiest times for tourism.<ref name=Islayweather/><ref>Newton (1995) p. 12</ref> Sunshine hours are typically highest around the coasts, especially to the west.<ref name=Met/>

