==Etymology==
Islay was probably recorded by [[Ptolemy]] as ''Epidion'',<ref name=W37>Watson (1994) p. 37</ref> the use of the "p" suggesting a [[British language|Brythonic]] or [[Picts|Pictish]] tribal name.<ref>Watson (1994) p. 45</ref> In the seventh century [[Adomn<U+00E1>n]] referred to the island as ''Ilea''<ref name=W85>Watson (1994) p. 85-86</ref> and the name  occurs in early Irish records as ''Ile'' and as ''<U+00CD>l'' in [[Old Norse]]. The root is not Gaelic and of unknown origin.<ref name=G2487/>{{#tag:ref|Mac an T<U+00E0>illeir (2003) suggests that "if this is a Gaelic name it may be 'flank shaped'."<ref name=MacanT67>Mac an T<U+00E0>illeir (2003) p. 67</ref>|group="Note"}} In poetic language Islay is known as ''Banr<U+00EC>gh Innse Gall'',<ref name=Newton11/> or ''Banr<U+00EC>gh nan Eilean''<ref>[http://www.hial.co.uk/islay-airport/visitors/ "Visitors"]. Highlands and Islands Airports. Retrieved 22 Mar 2012.</ref> usually translated as "Queen of the Hebrides"{{#tag:ref|''Banr<U+00EC>gh Innse Gall'' is literally "Queen of the islands of the foreigners" and ''Banr<U+00EC>gh nan Eilean'' means "Queen of the islands".|group="Note"}} and  ''Eilean uaine <U+00CC>le'' <U+2013> the "green isle of Islay"<ref name=MacanT67/> A native of Islay is called an ''<U+00CC>leach'', pronounced {{IPA-gd|<U+02C8>i<U+02D0>l<U+0259>x|}}.<ref name=MacanT67/>
[[File:Resettlement houses in central Port Charlotte - geograph.org.uk - 1422092.jpg|thumb|left|[[Port Charlotte, Islay|Port Charlotte]], founded in 1828<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 91</ref>]]
The obliteration of pre-Norse names is almost total and place names on the island are a mixture of Norse and later Gaelic and [[English language|English]] influences.<ref>Jennings and Kruse (2007) pp. 83<U+2013>84</ref><ref>King and Cotter  (2012) p. 4</ref> Port Askaig is from the Norse ''ask-v<U+00ED>k'', meaning "ash tree bay" and the common suffix -bus is from the Norse ''b<U+00F3>lsta<U+00F0>r'', meaning "farm".<ref>King and Cotter  (2012) p. 6</ref> Gaelic names, or their anglicised versions such as Ardnave Point, from ''<U+00C0>ird an Naoimh'', "height of the saint" are very common.<ref>King and Cotter  (2012) pp. 34, 36<U+2013>43</ref> Several of the villages were developed in the 18th and 19th centuries and English is a stronger influence in their names as a result. Port Charlotte for example, was named after Lady Charlotte Campbell, daughter of the island's then owner, [[Daniel Campbell (d. 1753)|Daniel Campbell of Shawfield]].<ref>King and Cotter  (2012) p. 31</ref>

==Prehistory==
[[File:Dun Nosebridge.jpg|thumb|[[Dun Nosebridge]] from the south]]
The earliest settlers on Islay were nomadic [[hunter-gatherer]]s who may have first arrived during the [[Mesolithic period]] after the retreat of the [[Pleistocene]] ice caps. A flint [[arrowhead]], which was found in a field near [[Bridgend, Islay|Bridgend]] in 1993 and dates from 10,800 BC, is amongst the earliest evidence of a human presence found so far in Scotland.<ref>Mithen (2006) pp. 197<U+2013>98</ref>{{#tag:ref|At the time this [[Ahrensburg culture|Ahrensburgian]] flint was the oldest find in Scotland<ref>Moffat (2005) p. 42</ref> but a subsequent discovery at [[Biggar, South Lanarkshire|Biggar]] predates it by over a millennium.<ref>[http://www.archaeology.co.uk/articles/features/howburn-farm-excavating-scotlands-first-people.htm "Howburn Farm: Excavating Scotland<U+2019>s first people"] Current Archaeology. Retrieved 21 Aug 2011.</ref>|group="Note"}} Other finds have been dated to 7000 BC using [[radiocarbon dating]] of shells and debris from [[kitchen midden]]s.<ref name="Mesolithic2">Storrie (1997) p. 28</ref><ref name="Mesolithic">Jupp (1994) p. 10</ref> By the [[Neolithic]], settlements had become more permanent,<ref name="neolithic">Storrie (1997) p. 29</ref> allowing for the construction of several communal monuments.<ref name="neolithic monuments">Jupp (1994) p. 11</ref>

The most spectacular prehistoric structure on the island is [[Dun Nosebridge]]. This {{convert|375|m2|sqft}} [[Iron Age]] fort occupies a prominent crag and has commanding views of the surrounding landscape. The name's origin is probably a mixture of Gaelic and Old Norse: ''Dun'' in the former language means "fort" and ''knaus-borg'' in the latter means "fort on the crag".<ref>Newton (1995) p. 26</ref> There is no evidence that Islay was ever subject to [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] military control although small numbers of finds such as a coin and a brooch from the third century AD suggest links of some kind with the intermittent [[Scotland during the Roman Empire|Roman presence]] on the mainland.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 17</ref> The ruins of a [[broch]] at D<U+00F9>n Bhoraraic south east of Ballygrant and the remains of numerous [[Atlantic roundhouse]]s indicate the influences of northern Scotland, where these forms of building originate.<ref name=Caldwell19/><ref>Armit, Ian "The Iron Age" in Omand (2006) pp. 52<U+2013>53</ref> There are also various [[crannog]]s on Islay, including sites in Loch Ardnave, Loch Ballygrant and Loch Allallaidh in the south east where a stone causeway leading out to two adjacent islands is visible beneath the surface of the water.<ref name=OS/><ref name=Caldwell19>Caldwell (2011) pp. 137<U+2013>38</ref>

There is some controversy about the nature of the relationship between the indigenous peoples of Ireland and south west Scotland during the late Iron Age. The widely accepted theory is that the latter became populated by immigrants from the former, replacing an earlier culture, although it has also been suggested that the Gaels in this part of Scotland were [[Indigenous peoples|indigenous]] to the area.<ref>Woolf (2012) p. 1</ref>

==History==
[[File:Port nan Gallan, on the Mull of Oa, Isle of Islay - geograph.org.uk - 92883.jpg|thumb|left|Port nan Gallan, [[The Oa]], with [[Kintyre]], mainland Scotland, in the far distance]]

===Dalriada===
By the 6th century AD Islay, along with much of mainland Argyll, lay within the Gaelic kingdom of [[D<U+00E1>l Riata]] with strong links to Ireland and, according to the  ''[[Senchus fer n-Alban]]'' ("The History of the Men of Scotland"), was ruled by the kin group [[Cen<U+00E9>l n<U+00D3>engusa]]. In 627 the son of a king of the Irish [[U<U+00ED> Echach Cobo|U<U+00ED> Ch<U+00F3>elbad]], a branch of the [[D<U+00E1>l nAraidi]] kingdom of Ulster, was killed on Islay at the unidentified location of Ard-Corann by a warrior in an army led by King [[Connad Cerr]] of the [[Corcu R<U+00E9>ti]], a kindred based in [[Cowal]] on the mainland of Scotland.<ref name=Caldwell21>Caldwell (2011) pp. 21<U+2013>22</ref> The ''Senchus'' also lists what is believed to be the oldest reference to a naval battle in the [[British Isles]]<U+2014>a brief record of an engagement between rival D<U+00E1>l Riatan groups in 719.<ref>Rodger (1997) p. 5</ref>

There is evidence of another kindred on Islay, the Cen<U+00E9>l Conchride, descended from a brother of the legendary D<U+00E1>l Riatan king [[Fergus M<U+00F3>r mac Eirc|Fergus M<U+00F3>r]] but its existence seems to have been brief and the four hundred and thirty households of the island are later said to have been divided between three great-grandsons of the eponymous founder of Cen<U+00E9>l n<U+00D3>engus: Lugaid, Connal and Gal<U+00E1>n.<ref name=Caldwell21/>

===Norse influence and the Kingdom of the Isles===
[[File:Standing stone, Finlaggan - geograph.org.uk - 753904.jpg|thumb|[[Standing stone]] at Carragh Bh<U+00E0>n, said to mark the grave of [[Godred Crovan]], [[Kingdom of the Isles|King of the Isles]]<ref name=Campbell89>Graham-Campbell and Batey (1998) p. 89</ref> The ruins on Eilean M<U+00F2>r, [[Finlaggan]] are visible in the background.]]
The arrival of Scandinavian settlers on the western seaboard of Scotland in the ninth century had a long-lasting effect. For the next four centuries and more all the islands of the west fell under the control of various rulers of the [[Kingdom of the Isles]] most of whom were of Norse origin. As is the case in the [[Northern Isles]], the derivation of place names suggests a complete break from the past. Jennings and Kruse (2009) conclude that  although there were settlements prior to the Norse arrival "there is no evidence from the [[wikt:onomasticon|onomasticon]] that the inhabitants of these settlements ever existed".<ref>Jennings and Kruse (2009) p. 140</ref> Gaelic continued to exist as a spoken language in the southern Hebrides throughout the Norse period, but the [[toponymy|place name evidence]] suggests it had a lowly status, possibly indicating an enslaved population.<ref>Jennings and Kruse (2007) p. 86</ref>

[[Godred Crovan]] was one of the [[Norse-Gael]] [[List of rulers of the Kingdom of the Isles|rulers]] of this Hebridean [[thalassocracy|sea kingdom]] who had a connection with Islay. His origins are obscure. The ''[[Chronicles of Mann]]'' call him the son of Harald the Black of Ysland, (his place or origin variously interpreted as Islay, [[Ireland]] or [[Iceland]]) and state he "so tamed the Scots that no one who built a ship or boat dared use more than three iron bolts".<ref name=Duffy04>Duffy, Se<U+00E1>n (2004) "Godred Crovan (d. 1095)". ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''. Oxford University Press.</ref><ref>MacDonald (2007) p. 62</ref> Godred also became [[Kings of Dublin|King of Dublin]] at an unknown date although in  1094 he was driven out of the city by [[Muircheartach Ua Briain]], later known as [[High King of Ireland]], according to the ''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]''. He died "of pestilence" on Islay the following year.<ref name=Duffy04/><ref name=D108>Duffy (1992) p. 108</ref><ref name=Woolf0513>Woolf (2005) p. 13</ref> A local tradition suggests that a [[standing stone]] at Carragh Bh<U+00E0>n just north of Loch Finlaggan marks Godred Crovan's grave. A genuine 11th century Norse grave-slab was found at D<U+00F3>id Mh<U+00E0>iri in 1838, although it was not associated with a burial. The slab is decorated with foliage in the style of  [[Ringerike]] Viking art and an Irish-style cross, the former being unique in [[Scandinavian Scotland]].<ref name=Campbell89/>

In the 12th century a grand-daughter of  Godred Crovan's married the ambitious [[Somerled]], a [[Norse-Gael]] Argyll nobleman. [[Godred II Olafsson|Godred Olafsson]], a grandson of Crovan, was an increasingly unpopular King of the Isles at the time and Somerled was spurred into action. The two fought the [[Battle of Epiphany]] in the seas off Islay in January 1156.{{#tag:ref|Various locations have been suggested for the battle, including west of the Rinns and north of Rubh' a' Mhail. Marsden (2008) concludes that a location at the north end of the Sound of Islay is most likely.<ref name=Marsden84>Marsden (2008) p. 84</ref>|group="Note"}} The result was a bloody [[stalemate]], and the island kingdom was temporarily divided, with Somerled taking control of the southern Hebrides. Two years later Somerled completely ousted Godred and re-united the kingdom, but the divide was re-established after the former's death in 1164.<ref name=Marsden84/><ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 31</ref><ref name=G917>Gregory (1881) pp. 9<U+2013>17</ref> His [[Clann Somhairle]] descendants continued to describe themselves as "King of the Sudreys" until the 13th century but following the 1266 [[Treaty of Perth]] the Hebrides were yielded to the Kingdom of Scotland.<ref>Hunter (2000) pp. 110<U+2013>111</ref><ref>Woolf, Alex  "The Age of the Sea-Kings: 900<U+2013>1300" in Omand (2006) pp. 108<U+2013>09</ref>

===Scottish rule===
====Lords of the Isles====
[[File:Amie mac Ruari.jpg|thumb|350px|left|The descent of [[Amy of Garmoran|Amie Macruari]] and [[John of Islay, Lord of the Isles|John of Islay]] from [[Somerled]]]]
Somerled's descendants became the rulers of various powerful [[Scottish clan|clans]], including the [[Clan MacDougall|MacDougalls]], [[Clan Donald]] and the [[Clan Macruari|Macruaris]]. [[Alexander of Argyll|Alexander MacDougall]]'s support of the opponents of King [[Robert the Bruce]] led to the forfeiture of his lands and they were distributed between [[Aonghas <U+00D3>g of Islay|Aonghas <U+00D3>g MacDonald of Islay]] and the chief of the Macruaris, Ruaidhri mac Ailein, who also held much of [[Lorne, Scotland|Lorne]], parts of [[Lochaber]], [[Garmoran]] and the North Isles.<ref name=Gregory24>Gregory (1881) p. 24</ref> These estates were eventually inherited by  [[Amy of Garmoran|Amie Macruairi of Garmoran]].<ref>Gregory (1881) pp. 26<U+2013>27</ref><ref>Lee (1920) p. 82</ref><ref name=O124/> She had married her MacDonald cousin [[John of Islay, Lord of the Isles|John of Islay]]  in the 1330s,<ref name=H127/> and he now controlled significant stretches of the western seaboard of Scotland from [[Morvern]] to [[Loch Hourn]] and the whole of the Hebrides save for [[Skye]].<ref name=O124>Oram, Richard "The Lordship of the Isles, 1336<U+2013>1545" in Omand (2006) pp. 124<U+2013>26</ref> From 1336 onwards John began to style himself ''Dominus Insularum''<U+2014>"[[Lord of the Isles]]", a title that implied a connection to the earlier Kings of  the Isles and by extension a degree of independence from the Scottish crown<ref name=O124/><ref name=H127>Hunter (2000) p. 127</ref><ref>Oram, Richard "The Lordship of the Isles, 1336<U+2013>1545" in Omand (2006) p. 123</ref> and this honorific was claimed by his heirs for several generations.<ref name=Caldwell38>Caldwell (2011) p. 38</ref>

Initially, the MacDonald Lords' power base was  on the shores of [[Loch Finlaggan]] in northeastern Islay. Successive chiefs of Clan Donald were proclaimed Lord of the Isles there and their advisory "Council of the Isles" met on Eilean na Comhairle.{{#tag:ref|Loch Finlaggan has two main islands. Eilean M<U+00F2>r was probably an early Christian centre and was fortified in the 13th and 14th centuries.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 169</ref> Eilean na Comhairle was originally a timber framed crannog, constructed in the 1st century BC.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 20</ref>|group="Note"}} However as their control of the west grew in strength the twin castles of [[Aros Castle|Aros]] and [[Ardtornish Castle|Ardtornish]] in the [[Sound of Mull]] had become the "heart of the Lordship" by the early 15th century.<ref>Oram, Richard "The Lordship of the Isles, 1336<U+2013>1545" in Omand (2006) p. 132</ref>

The [[Islay Charter]], a record of lands granted to an Islay resident, Brian Vicar MacKay, by [[Domhnall of Islay, Lord of the Isles]] in 1408, is one of the earliest records of [[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]] in public use, and is a significant historical document.<ref>{{cite news| work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]| url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/gaelic-documents-may-return-north-1.857694| title=Gaelic documents may return north| author=David Ross| date=10 May 2007| accessdate=23 Jan 2008}}</ref> In 1462, [[John of Islay, Earl of Ross]] struck an alliance with [[Edward IV of England]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Ardtornish-Westminster]].  The onset of the [[Wars of the Roses]] prevented Edward from fulfilling his obligations as an ally, and in 1493 MacDonald was compelled to forfeit his estates and titles to [[James IV of Scotland|James IV]].  After the forfeiture, James ordered Finlaggan demolished, its buildings razed, and the coronation stone destroyed to discourage any attempts at restoration of the Lordship.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 59</ref><ref>Caldwell, David (April 1996) [http://www.britarch.ac.uk/ba/ba13/BA13FEAT.HTML "Urbane savages of the Western Isles"]. ''British Archaeology''. No 13. Retrieved 26 April 2012.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The title "Lord of the Isles" itself survived and today the heir to the British throne, who is known as the [[Prince of Wales]] in all other parts of the [[British Commonwealth]], bears this title within Scotland.<ref>Dunbar, J.  (1981) ''The Lordship of the Isles in The Middle Ages in the Highlands''. Inverness Field Club. ISBN 978-0-9502612-1-8</ref>|group="Note"}} When [[Martin Martin]] visited Islay in the late 17th century he recorded a description of the coronations Finlaggan had once seen.{{#tag:ref|Martin wrote of the "isle Finlagan", that it is "famous for being once the court in which the great Macdonald, King of the Isles, had his residence; his houses, chapel, etc., are now ruinous. His guards de corps, called Lucht-taeh, kept guard on the lake side nearest to the isle; the walls of their houses are still to be seen there. The High Court of Judicature, consisting of fourteen, sat always here; and there was an appeal to them from all the Courts in the isles: the eleventh share of the sum in debate was due to the principal judge. There was a big stone of seven feet square, in which there was a deep impression made to receive the feet of Macdonald; for he was crowned King of the Isles standing in this stone, and swore that he would continue his vassals in the possession of their lands, and do exact justice to all his subjects: and then his father<U+2019>s sword was put into his hand. The Bishop of Argyll and seven priests anointed him king, in presence of all the heads of the tribes in the isles and continent, and were his vassals; at which time the orator rehearsed a catalogue of his ancestors, etc."<ref>Martin (1703) "Jura"</ref>|group="Note"}}

====16th and 17th centuries====
[[File:Another view of Dunyvaig Castle - geograph.org.uk - 865592.jpg|thumb|The ruins of [[Dunnyvaig Castle]], a [[Clan MacDonald of Dunnyveg|MacDonald]] stronghold in the 16th century]]
Initially dispossessed in the wake of royal opposition to the Lordship, [[Clan MacDonald of Dunnyveg]]'s holdings in Islay were restored in 1545.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 61</ref>  In 1549, [[Donald Monro (Dean)|Dean Monro]] observed that the island was fertile, fruitful, and full of natural pastures, with good hunting and plentiful salmon and seals. He also referred to [[Dunyvaig Castle]] in the south east, controlled by Clan  Donald and [[Loch Gorm Castle]] on Eilean M<U+00F2>r in Loch Gorm to the west, "now usurped be M<U+2019>Gillayne of Doward".<ref name=Munro55>Monro (1549) "Ila" No. 55</ref>{{#tag:ref|With regard to the castles of Islay Monro wrote: "In this iyle there is strenths castells; the first is callit Dunowaik, biggit on ane craig at the sea side, on the southeist part of the countery pertaining to the Clandonald of Kintyre; second is callit the castle of Lochgurne, quhilk is biggit ill ane iyle within the said fresche water loche far fra land, pertaining of auld to the Clandonald of Kintyre, now usurped be M<U+2019>Gillayne of Doward. Ellan Forlagan, in the middle of Ila, ane faire iyle in fresche water.<ref name=Munro55/>|group="Note"}} This implied dispute with the [[Maclean of Duart|Macleans]] continued and they were expelled from Loch Gorm by force in 1578  and defeated at the [[Battle of Traigh Ghruinneart]] in 1598. However, a clash with the Irish branch of the family led by [[Sorley Boy MacDonnell]] and their unpopularity in [[Edinburgh]] (where their use of Gaelic was regarded as barbaric) weakened the MacDonald grip on their southern Hebridean possessions. In 1608 the [[James VI and I|Scottish crown]] mounted an expedition to subdue them and then in 1614 handed Islay over to Sir John [[Clan Campbell of Cawdor|Campbell of Cawdor]] in return for an undertaking to pacify the island.<ref>Caldwell (2011) pp. 62<U+2013>64</ref><ref>Haswell-Smith (2004) pp. 42<U+2013>43</ref> This the Campbells eventually achieved although a setback occurred during the [[Scotland in the Wars of the Three Kingdoms|Civil War]] when a [[Covenanter]] army under [[David Leslie, Lord Newark|Sir David Leslie]] arrived on the island in 1647. They besieged a royalist garrison at Dunnyvaig and laid waste to the island.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 68</ref> It was not until 1677 that the Campbells felt sufficiently at ease there to construct Islay House at Bridgend as their principal (and unfortified) island residence.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 66, 74</ref> The structure was built for Sir Hugh Campbell of Cawdor and is now a [[List of Category A listed buildings in Argyll and Bute|Category A listed building]].<ref>[http://hsewsf.sedsh.gov.uk/hslive/portal.hsstart?P_HBNUM=12142 "Islay House"]. Historic Scotland. Retrieved 11 September 2012.</ref>

===British era===
[[File:Cottage on Islay (18thC).JPG|thumb|A cottage on Islay from [[Thomas Pennant]]'s ''A Tour in Scotland and Voyage to the Hebrides'', published in 1774.]]
At the beginning of the 18th century much of the population of Argyll  was to be found dispersed in small clachans of farming families<ref>Morrison, Alex "Rural Settlement: an Archaeological Viewpoint" in Omand (2006) p. 110</ref> and only two villages of any size<U+2014>Killarow near Bridgend and Lagavulin<U+2014>existed on Islay at the time.<ref name=Caldwell75>Caldwell (2011) pp. 75<U+2013>76</ref> (Killarow had a church and [[tolbooth]] and houses for merchants and craft workers but was razed in the 1760s to "improve" the grounds of Islay House.)<ref name=Caldwell75/> The agricultural economy was dependent on arable farming including staples such as barley and oats supplemented with stock-rearing. The carrying capacity of the island was recorded at over  6,600 cows and 2,200 horses in a 1722 rental listing.<ref>Caldwell (2011) p. 70</ref>

In 1726 Islay was purchased by Daniel Campbell of Shawfield.<ref>[http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Campbell,_Daniel_%281671%3F-1753%29_%28DNB00%29 "Campbell, Daniel (1671?<U+2013>1753)"] Dictionary of National Biography (1904). Retrieved 19 April 2012.</ref><ref name=Caldwell79>Caldwell (2011) p. 79</ref> It remained in his family's ownership until 1853 when it was sold to James Morrison of [[Berkshire]], ancestor of the third [[Baron Margadale]], who still owns a substantial portion of the island.<ref name=Caldwell79/> A defining aspect of 19th century Argyll was the gradual improvement of  transport infrastructure.<ref>Duncan, P. J. "The Industries of Argyll: Tradition and Improvement" in Omand (2006) p. 151</ref> Roads were built, the [[Crinan canal]] shortened the sea distance to [[Glasgow]] and the numerous traditional ferry crossings were augmented by new quays. Rubble piers were built at several locations on Islay and a new harbour was constructed at Port Askaig.<ref>Duncan, P. J. "The Industries of Argyll: Tradition and Improvement" in Omand (2006) pp. 152<U+2013>4</ref>
[[File:American Monument, Mull of Oa - geograph.org.uk - 592728.jpg|thumb|left|The American Monument on the [[The Oa|Mull of Oa]] commemorates the sinking of two troop ships during [[World War I]]]]
Initially, a sense of optimism in the fishing and cattle trades prevailed and the population expanded, partly as a result of the 18th century [[kelp]] boom and the introduction of the potato as a staple.<ref>Duncan, P. J. "The Industries of Argyll: Tradition and Improvement" in Omand (2006) pp. 156<U+2013>57</ref> The population of the island had been estimated at 5,344 in 1755 and grew to over  15,000 by 1841. However, the sundering of the relationship between the landowners and the island's residents proved consequential. When the estate owners realised they could make more money from sheep farming than from the indigenous small farmers, wholesale [[Highland Clearances|Clearances]] became commonplace. 400 people emigrated from Islay in 1863 alone, some for purely economic reasons, but many others having been forced off the land their predecessors had farmed for centuries. In 1891 the census recorded only 7,375 citizens, with many evictees making new homes in Canada,  the United States and elsewhere. The population continued to decline for much of the 20th century and today is about 3,500.<ref name=HSmith41/><ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay_clearances.html "The Clearances on Islay in the 1800s"] IslayInfo. Retrieved 20 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.cranntara.org.uk/clear.htm "Highland Clearances"]. Cranntara. Retrieved 20 April 2012.</ref>

During [[World War I]] two troop ships foundered off Islay within a few months of one another in 1918. The American vessel [[SS Tuscania (1914)|SS ''Tuscania'']] was torpedoed by UB-77 on 5 February with the loss of over 160 lives and now lies in deep water {{convert|6.4|km|mi|0}} west of the Mull of Oa.<ref>Baird (1995) pp. 57<U+2013>58</ref> On 6 October [[HMS Otranto|HMS ''Otranto'']] was involved in a collision with HMS ''Kashmir'' in heavy seas while [[convoy]]ing troops from New York. ''Otranto'' lost steering and drifted towards the west coast of the Rinns. Answering her SOS the [[Yarrow M class destroyer|destroyer]] [[HMS Mounsey (1915)|HMS ''Mounsey'']] attempted to come alongside and managed to rescue over 350 men. Nonetheless, the ''Otranto'' was wrecked on the shore near Machir Bay with a total loss of 431 lives.<ref>Baird (1995) pp. 80<U+2013>83</ref> A monument was erected on the coast of The Oa by the [[American Red Cross]] to commemorate the sinking of these two ships.<ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay_oa_peninsula.html "The Oa Peninsula"]. IslayInfo. Retrieved 21 April 2012.</ref>

During [[World War II]], the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] built an airfield at [[Islay Airport|Glenegedale]] which later became the civil [[EGPI|airport]] for Islay. There was also an [[RAF Coastal Command]] [[flying boat]] base at [[Bowmore]] from 13 March 1941 using Loch Indaal.<ref>[http://www.rafcommands.com/Coastal/119C.html "No 119 Squadron RAF"]. RAF Commands. Retrieved 23 Jan 2008.</ref> In 1944 an [[No. 422 Squadron RCAF|RCAF 422 Squadron]] [[Short Sunderland|Sunderland flying boat's]] crew were rescued after their aircraft landed off Bowmore but broke from her moorings in a gale and sank.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.castlearchdale.net/id22.html| title=422 Faces|publisher=Castle Archdale, Northern Ireland Coastal Command| accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref> There was an RAF [[Chain Home]] radar station at Saligo Bay and RAF [[Chain Home Low]] station at Kilchiaran.<ref>[http://www.scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search_item/index.php?service=RCAHMS&id=141169 "Islay, Saligo, Chain Home and Type 7000 Chain Radar Station"]. Scotland's Places. Retrieved 21 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/204701/contribution/islay+kilchiaran+radar+station/FNL5959540566/ "Islay, Kilchirian, Radar Station"]. Canmore. Retrieved 21 April 2012.</ref>

==Economy==
The mainstays of the modern Islay economy are agriculture and fishing, [[Distillation|distilling]] and tourism.<ref name=Caldwell95>Caldwell (2011) p. 95</ref>

===Agriculture and fishing===
[[File:Portaskaig.jpg|thumb|Looking over to the [[Paps of Jura]] from [[Port Askaig]]]]
Much of Islay remains in the hands of a few non-resident estate owners and sheep farming and the few dairy cattle herds are run by tenant farmers.<ref name=Caldwell95/> Islay has some fine wild [[brown trout]] and [[Atlantic salmon|salmon]] fishing<ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay_fishing.html "Fishing on Islay <U+2013> Where to catch Brown Trout"]. IslayInfo. Retrieved 13 April 2012.</ref> and in September 2003 the European Fishing Competition was held on five of the island's numerous lochs: this was "the biggest fishing event ever to be held in Scotland".<ref name=Fishing>[http://www.fishing-argyll.co.uk/isle-of-islay.html "Isle of Islay"] Fishing-Argyll. Retrieved 13 April 2012.</ref> Sea [[angling]] is also popular especially off the west coast and over the many [[shipwreck]]s around the coast.<ref name=Fishing/> There are about 20 commercial boats with crab, [[lobster]] and [[scallop]] fishing undertaken from Port Askaig, Port Ellen and Porthahaven.<ref>Newton (1995) p. 82</ref><ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay-sea-geography-history.html "Islay and the Sea <U+2013> Geography and History"]. IslayInfo. Retrieved 13 April 2012.</ref>

===Distilling===
{{main|Islay whisky}}
[[File:Distilleries Islay updated 2011.png|thumb|left|Islay's distilleries]]
Islay is one of five [[Scotch whisky|whisky]] distilling localities and regions in Scotland whose identity is protected by law.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2009/2890/contents/made "The Scotch Whisky Regulations 2009"]. The National Archives. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref>  There are eight active distilleries and the industry is the island's second largest employer after agriculture.<ref>Newton (1995) p. 32</ref><ref>[http://www.scotch-whisky.org.uk/understanding-scotch/whisky-regions-tours/ "Whisky Regions & Tours"]. Scotch Whisky Association. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref> Those on the south of the island produce [[Malt whisky|malts]] with a very strong [[peat]]y flavour, considered to be the most intensely flavoured of all whiskies. From east to west they are [[Ardbeg]], [[Lagavulin Single Malt|Lagavulin]], and [[Laphroaig]]. On the north of the island [[Bowmore Single Malt|Bowmore]], [[Bruichladdich]], [[Caol Ila]] and [[Bunnahabhain]] are produced, which are substantially lighter in taste.<ref>[http://www.information-britain.co.uk/food/foodlegends/Islay%20Whisky/ "Islay Whisky"]  information-britain.co.uk. Retrieved 4 January 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.islaywhiskysociety.com/ "Home"]. Islay Whisky. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref>  [[Kilchoman Distillery|Kilchoman]] is a [[microdistillery]] opened in 2005 on the west coast of the Rinns.<ref>[http://www.scotchwhisky.net/distilleries/kilchoman.htm "Kilchoman Scotch Whisky Distillery"]. ScotchWhisky.net. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref>
[[File:Lagavulin Distillery - geograph.org.uk - 113329.jpg|right|thumb|[[Lagavulin Single Malt|Lagavulin]] distillery]]
The oldest record of a legal distillery on the island refers to Bowmore in 1779 and at one time there were up to 23 distilleries in operation.<ref name=Newton33>Newton (1995) p. 33</ref> For example, [[Port Charlotte (distillery)|Port Charlotte distillery]] operated from 1829 to 1929<ref name=IslayinfoPortC>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay_port_charlotte_distillery.html "Port Charlotte Distillery"].  IslayInfo. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref> and [[Port Ellen Single Malt|Port Ellen]] is also closed although it remains in business as a [[malthouse|malting]].<ref name=Newton33/>  In March 2007 Bruichladdich announced that they would reopen Port Charlotte distillery using equipment from the Inverleven distillery<ref name=IslayinfoPortC/> and Bruichladdich is also noteworthy as the only distillery which bottles its malts on Islay.<ref>[http://www.scotlandwhisky.com/distilleries/islay/Bruichladdich "Bruichladdich Whisky Distillery Islay"]. Scotland and Whisky. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref>

===Tourism===
Some 45,000 summer visitors arrive per annum by ferry and a further 11,000 by air,<ref>Keay and Keay (1994) p. 548</ref> the main attractions being the scenery, history, [[ornithology|bird watching]] and the world famous whiskies.<ref>[http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,RGN983vs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html "The Isle of Islay"]. Visit Scotland.  Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref> The distilleries operate various shops, tours, visitor centres etc.<ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay_whisky_distilleries.html "Islay Malt Whisky & Islay Distilleries"]. IslayInfo. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref> and the Finlaggan Trust has a visitor centre which is open daily during the summer.<ref>[http://www.finlaggan.com/visit.asp "Visit Finlaggan"]. The Finlaggan Trust. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref>

===Renewable energy===
The location of Islay, exposed to the full force of the North Atlantic, has led to it being the site of a pioneering, and Scotland's first, [[wave power]] station near Portnahaven. The [[Islay LIMPET]] (Land Installed Marine Powered Energy Transformer) wave power generator was designed and built by Wavegen and researchers from the [[Queen's University of Belfast]], and was financially backed by the European Union. Known as Limpet 500, due to cabling constraints its capacity is limited to providing up to 150&nbsp;kW of electricity into the island's grid.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wavegen.co.uk/pdf/Consruction,commission%20&%20operation%20of%20LIMPET.pdf| format=pdf| author=Tom Heath| title=The Construction, Commissioning and Operation of the LIMPET Wave Energy Collector| publisher=Wavegen| accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref> In 2000 it became the world's first commercial wave power station. In March 2011 the largest [[tidal power|tidal array]] in the world was approved by the Scottish Government with 10 planned turbines predicted to generate enough power for over 5,000 homes. The project will be located in the [[Sound of Islay]] which offers both strong currents and shelter from storms.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-12767211 "Islay to get major tidal power scheme"] (17 Mar 2011) BBC Scotland. Retrieved 17 Mar 2011.</ref>

===Transport===
[[File:Finlaggan approaching Kennacraig.jpg|thumb|left|[[Caledonian MacBrayne]]'s [[MV Finlaggan|MV ''Finlaggan'']]]]
Many of the roads on the island are single-track with passing places. The two main roads are the [[A846 road|A846]] from Ardbeg to Port Askaig via Port Ellen and Bowmore, and the [[A847 road|A847]] which runs down the east coast of the Rhinns.<ref name=OS/> The island has its own bus service provided by Islay Coaches and Glenegedale Airport offers flights to and from [[Glasgow International Airport]] and on a less regular basis to [[Oban Airport|Oban]] and [[Colonsay Airport|Colonsay]].<ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/travel.html "Islay Travel and Local Transport Information"]. IslayInfo. Retrieved 22 April 2012.</ref>

[[Caledonian MacBrayne]] operate regular ferry services to Port Ellen and Port Askaig from [[Kennacraig]], taking about two hours. Ferries to Port Askaig also run on to [[Scalasaig]] on [[Colonsay]] and, on summer Wednesdays, to [[Oban]]. The purpose-built vessel, {{MV|Finlaggan}} entered service in 2011.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.calmac.co.uk/on-board-ships-guide/MV%20Finlaggan%20Information%20Leaflet.pdf| title=MV Finlaggan| format = pdf|publisher=[[Caledonian MacBrayne]]| accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref> ASP Ship Management Ltd operate a small car ferry on behalf of [[Argyll and Bute|Argyll & Bute Council]] from Port Askaig to [[Feolin]] on [[Jura, Scotland|Jura]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.islayjura.com/?page_id=85| title=Travelling to Islay & Jura| publisher=Visit Islay Jura| accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref>
[[File:Portellen lighthouse.jpg|thumb|The lighthouse at Carraig Fhada, [[Port Ellen]]]]
There are various [[lighthouse]]s on and around Islay as an aid to navigation. These include the Rinns of Islay light built on Orsay in 1825 by [[Robert Stevenson (civil engineer)|Robert Stevenson]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nlb.org.uk/LighthouseLibrary/Lighthouse/Rinns-of-Islay/| title=Rinns of Islay| publisher=[[Northern Lighthouse Board]]| accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> Ruvaal at the north western tip of Islay constructed in 1859,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nlb.org.uk/LighthouseLibrary/Lighthouse/Ruvaal/| title=Ruvaal| publisher=[[Northern Lighthouse Board]]| accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> Carraig Fhada at Port Ellen, which has an unusual design,<ref>Newton (1995) p. 16</ref> and [[Dubh Artach]], an isolated rock tower some {{convert|35|km|mi}} to the north west of Ruvaal.

===Other activities===
Since 1973 the ''Ileach'' has been delivering news to the people of Islay every fortnight and was named community newspaper of the year in 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.highland.gov.uk/yourcouncil/news/newsreleases/2007/January/2007-01-18-00.htm| title=Shetland Times Retains Newspaper Of The Year Award| publisher = Highland Council|date=18 January 2007| accessdate=23 Jan 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.firstport.org.uk/directory/org/878 "Islay & Jura Council for Voluntary Service <U+2013> Bowmore"] Firstport. Retrieved 13 April 2012.</ref> The Islay Ales Brewery brews various [[real ale]]s at its premises near  Bridgend.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.islayales.com/| title=Ales from the Isle of Malts| publisher=Islay Ales| accessdate=2008-01-23}}</ref> In the early 21st century a campus of [[Sabhal M<U+00F2>r Ostaig]] was set up on Islay, [[Ionad Chaluim Chille <U+00CC>le]], which teaches Gaelic language, culture and heritage.<ref>[http://en.islay-gaelic.net/ "An open door to Gaelic language and culture"]. Ionad Chaluim Chille <U+00CC>le. Retrieved 13 April 2012.</ref> The Port M<U+00F2>r community centre at Port Charlotte, which is equipped with a micro wind turbine and a ground source heating system, is the creation of local [[development trust]] Iomairt Chille Chomain.<ref>[http://islandofislay.co.uk/about-us.php "About Us"]. Iomairt Chille Chomain. Retrieved 15 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.dtascot.org.uk/content/directory-of-members/iomairt-chille-chomain "Iomairt Chille Chomain"]. [[DTAS|DTA Scotland]]. Retrieved 15 April 2012.</ref>

==Gaelic language==
Islay has historically been a very strong Gaelic speaking area. Both in the 1901 and 1921 census, all parishes in Islay were reported to be over 75 per cent Gaelic speaking. By 1971, the Rhinns had dropped to 50-74% speakers and the rest of Islay to 25-49% overall.<ref name=MacT>Mac an T<U+00E0>illeir, Iain (2004) [http://www.linguae-celticae.org/dateien/Gaelic_1901-2001.ppt  ''1901-2001 Gaelic in the Census''] (PowerPoint) Linguae Celticae. Retrieved 19 September 2012.</ref> By 1991 about a third of the island's population were Gaelic speakers.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2001/09/195 "Boost for Islay Gaelic centre"] (11 September 2001) Scottish Government. Retrieved 3 August 2008.</ref> In the 2001 census this had dropped to 24% which, while a low figure overall, nonetheless made it the most strongly Gaelic-speaking island in [[Argyll and Bute]] after Tiree, with the highest percentage recorded in Portnahaven (32%) and the lowest in Gortontaoid (17%), with the far north and south of the island being the weakest areas in general.<ref name=MacT/>

The Islay dialect is distinctive. It patterns strongly with other Argyll dialects, especially those of Jura, Colonsay and [[Kintyre]].<ref>Grannd (2000) pp. 61<U+2013>65</ref> Amongst its distinctive phonological features are the shift from long /a<U+02D0>/ to /<U+025B><U+02D0>/, a high degree of retention of long /e<U+02D0>/, the shift of dark /l<U+032A><U+02E0>/ to /t<U+032A>/, the lack of intrusive /t<U+032A>/ in ''sr'' groups (for example /s<U+032A><U+027E>o<U+02D0>n/ "nose" rather than /s<U+032A>t<U+032A><U+027E>o<U+02D0>n/)<ref>Grannd (2000) pp: 14, 73; 54<U+2013>55, 139; 59, 146; 51, 134</ref> and the retention of the [[Lenition|unlenited]] past-tense particle ''d''' (for example, ''d'<U+00E8>irich'' "rose" instead of ''dh'<U+00E8>irich'').<ref>Grannd (2000) p. 135</ref> It sits within a group of [[Isogloss|lexical isoglosses]] (i.e. words distinctive to a certain area) with strong similarities to southern Gaelic and northern [[Irish language|Irish]] dialects. Examples are ''dhuit'' "to you" (instead of the more common ''dhut''),<ref>Grannd (2000) pp. 17, 78</ref> the formula ''gun robh math agad'' "thank you" (instead of the more common ''m<U+00F2>ran taing'' or ''tapadh leat'' but compare [[Irish language|Irish]] ''go raibh maith agat''),<ref>Grannd (2000) pp. 22, 86</ref> ''mand'' "able to" (instead of the more common ''urrainn'')<ref>Grannd (2000) pp. 26<U+2013>27, 94</ref> or ''deifir'' "hurry" (instead of the more common ''cabhag'', Irish ''deifir'').<ref>Grannd (2000) pp. 33, 107</ref>

==Religion==
[[File:Kildalton Cross - geograph.org.uk - 860780.jpg|thumb|border|left|[[Kildalton Cross]]]]
Associated with various Islay churches are [[cupstone]]s of uncertain age; these can be seen at Kilchoman Church, where the carved cross there is erected on one, and at Kilchiaran Church on the Rhinns. In historic times some may have been associated with pre-Christian wishing ceremonies or neo-pagan beliefs in the "[[Fairy|wee folk]]".<ref>Morris, Ronald W. B. (1969) "The Cup-and-Ring Marks and Similar Sculptures of Scotland: a Survey of the Southern Counties, Part II." ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries of Scotland'' '''100''' pp. 53, 55, 63</ref>

The early pioneers of Christianity in D<U+00E1>l Riata were [[Columba]] of Iona and [[Saint Moluag|Moluag]] of [[Lismore, Scotland|Lismore]].<ref>Fisher, Ian "The early Christian Period" in Omand (2006) p. 71</ref> The legacy of this period includes the 8th century [[Kildalton Cross]], Islay's "most famous treasure",<ref>Newton (1995) p. 37</ref> carved out of local [[epidiorite]].<ref>[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/251204/details/islay+kildalton+chapel+burial+ground+kildalton+great+cross/ "Kildalton Great Cross"] RCAHMS. Retrieved 10 April 2012.</ref> A carved cross of similar age, but much more heavily weathered can be found at Kilnave,<ref>{{cite web| title=Archaeology Notes on Kilnave| url=http://www.rcahms.gov.uk/pls/portal/newcanmore.details_gis?inumlink=37474| publisher=[[Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland|RCAHMS]]| accessdate=23 Jan 2008}}</ref> which may have served as a site of lay worship.<ref>Fisher, Ian "The early Christian Period" in Omand (2006) p. 82</ref> Although the first Norse settlers were pagan, Islay has a substantial number of sites of drystone or clay-mortared chapels with small burial grounds from the later Norse era.<ref>Fisher, Ian "The early Christian Period" in Omand (2006) p. 83</ref> In the 12th century the island became part of the [[Diocese of the Isles|Diocese of Sodor and the Isles]], which was re-established by King [[Olaf I Godredsson|Olaf Godredsson]].<ref>Bridgland, Nick "The Medieval Church in Argyll" in Omand (2006) p. 86</ref> The diocese fell within the jurisdiction of the [[Archdiocese of Nidaros]] and there were four principal churches on Islay in the  Norwegian ''prestegjeld'' model: Kilnaughton, Kildalton, Kilarrow and Kilmany.<ref name=Omand88>Bridgland, Nick "The Medieval Church in Argyll" in Omand (2006) pp. 88<U+2013>9</ref> In 1472 Islay became part of the [[Archdiocese of St Andrews]].<ref name=Omand88/>
[[File:Kilarrow round church.jpg|right|thumb|[[Kilarrow Parish Church]], [[Bowmore]]]]
[[Archibald Campbell, 5th Earl of Argyll]] was a strong supporter of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]], but there is little evidence that his beliefs were greeted with much enthusiasm by the islanders initially. At first there were only two reformed churches but in 1642 three parishes were created, based at Kilchoman, Kilarrow and a new church at Dunyvaig. By the end of the century there were seven churches including one on Nave Island.<ref>Caldwell (2011) pp. 68<U+2013>69</ref> [[Kilarrow Parish Church]] is round, as local folklore has it, to leave no corner for the devil to hide in. This "architectural gem" was constructed in 1767 by Daniel Campbell, the [[laird]] of Islay.<ref>Newton (1995) pp. 20<U+2013>21</ref> The [[kirk]] on the Rhinns of Islay is  St Kiaran's, located just outside the village of Port Charlotte and Port Ellen is served by St John's. There are a variety of other [[Church of Scotland]] churches and various other congregations on the island. [[Baptists]] meet in Port Ellen and in Bowmore, the [[Scottish Episcopal Church]] of [[St. Columba]] is located in Bridgend and the Islay Roman Catholic congregation also uses St. Columba's for its services.<ref>[http://www.islayinfo.com/islay_churches.html "Churches and Services on the Isle of Islay."] IslayInfo. Retrieved 23 Mar 2012.</ref>

==Media and the arts==
Islay was featured in some of the scenes of the 1954 film, ''[[The Maggie]]''<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047085/locations ''The Maggie''] Imdb. Retrieved 10 April 2012.</ref> and the 1942 documentary "[[Coastal Command (film)|Coastal Command]]" was partly filmed in Bowmore.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0034603/locations| title=Filming locations for "Coastal Command"| publisher=[[IMDb]]| accessdate= 23 Jan 2008}}</ref>

In 1967<U+2013>68, folk-rock singer Donovan included "The Isle of Islay" in his album, ''[[A Gift from a Flower to a Garden]]'', a song praising the pastoral beauties of the island.{{#tag:ref|It is claimed that Donovan wrote the song after being arrested for possession of [[marijuana]] and that "I had to leave, I had to get away from the publicity, so I took a plane north to Scotland, and on a northern island I found the peace, and I wrote this song."<ref>[http://donovan-unofficial.com/music/songs/isle_of_islay.html "Isle of Islay"] Donovan Unofficial. Retrieved 11 April 2012.</ref>|group="Note"}} "[[Westering Home]]" is a 20th century Scottish song about Islay written by [[Hugh S. Roberton]], derived from an earlier Gaelic song.<ref>[http://www.scottishpoetrylibrary.org.uk/poetry/poems/westering-home "Westering Home"]. Scottish Poetry Library. Retrieved 11 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.celticartscenter.com/Songs/Scottish/WesteringHome.html "Westering Home"]. Celtic Arts Center. Retrieved 11 April 2012.</ref>

In the 1990s the BBC adaptation of ''[[Para Handy]]'' was partly filmed in Port Charlotte and Bruichladdich and featured a race between the ''[[Vital Spark]]'' (Para Handy's [[Clyde puffer|puffer]]) and a rival along the length of Loch Indaal. In 2007, parts of the BBC [[Springwatch]] programme were recorded on Islay with [[Simon King (television)|Simon King]] being based on Islay. The British Channel 4 [[Time Team]] television series excavated at Finlaggan, the episode being first broadcast in 1995.<ref name="springwatch">{{cite web| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/animals/springwatch/programmes/| title=Springwatch| publisher=[[BBC]]| accessdate=23 Jan 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.visitscottishheartlands.com/stage_screen/mid_argyll.html "Mid-Argyll, Kintyre & Islay"]. Visit Scotland. Retrieved 12 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.channel4.com/programmes/time-team/episode-guide/series-2 "Time Teak: Series 2"]. Channel 4. Retrieved 12 April 2012.</ref>

In 2000, Japanese author [[Murakami Haruki]] visited the island to sample seven single malt whiskys on the island and later wrote a travel book called ''[[:ja:<U+3082><U+3057><U+50D5><U+3089><U+306E><U+3053><U+3068><U+3070><U+304C><U+30A6><U+30A3><U+30B9><U+30AD><U+30FC><U+3067><U+3042><U+3063><U+305F><U+306A><U+3089>|If our language were whiskey]]''.<!--Murakami Haruki uses the Irish spelling "whiskey" for some reason. See http://www.haruki-murakami.com  -->

==Wildlife==
[[File:bridgendwoods.JPG|thumb|left|Bridgend woods in January]]
Islay is home to many different species of wildlife and is especially known for its birds. Winter visiting [[Barnacle Goose]] numbers have reached 35,000 in recent years with as many as 10,000 arriving in a single day.  There are also up to 12,000 [[Greenland White-fronted Goose]] and smaller numbers of [[Brent Goose|Brent]], [[Pink-footed Goose|Pinkfooted]] and [[Canada Goose|Canada]] Geese are often found amongst these flocks. Other water-fowl include [[Whooper Swan|Whooper]] and [[Mute Swan|Mute]] Swans, [[Eider|Eider Duck]], [[Horned Grebe|Slavonian Grebe]], [[Common Goldeneye|Goldeneye]], [[Long-tailed Duck]] and [[Eurasian Wigeon|Wigeon]].<ref name=SOC>[http://www.the-soc.org.uk/islay-sites.htm "Birdwatching on Islay"]. Scottish Ornithologists' Club/''Scottish Bird News''. Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref> The elusive [[Corncrake]] and [[Sanderling]], [[Common Ringed Plover|Ringed Plover]] and [[Curlew Sandpiper]] are amongst the summer visitors.<ref name=SOC/> Resident birds include [[Red-billed Chough]], [[Hen Harrier]], [[Golden Eagle]], [[Peregrine Falcon]], [[Barn Owl]], [[Common Raven|Raven]], [[Eurasian Oystercatcher|Oystercatcher]] and [[Common Guillemot|Guillemot]].<ref name=SOC/>  The re-introduced [[White-tailed Eagle|White-tailed Sea Eagle]] is now seen regularly around the coasts.<ref>[http://www.naturetrek.co.uk/tour.aspx?id=165 "Islay and Jura"]. Naturetrek. Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref> In all, about 105 species breed on the island each year and between 100 and 120 different species can be seen at any one time.<ref name=SOC/>

A population of several thousand [[Red Deer]] inhabit the moors and hills, [[Fallow Deer]] can be found in the south east and [[Roe Deer]] are common on low-lying ground. [[European Otter|Otter]] are common around the coasts along and [[Harbor seal|Common]] and [[Grey Seal]] breed on Nave Island. Offshore, a variety of [[cetacean]]s are regularly recorded including [[Minke Whale]], [[Pilot Whale]], [[Killer Whale]] and [[Bottlenose dolphin|Bottle-nosed Dolphin]]. The only snake on Islay is the [[Vipera berus|Adder]]  and the [[Viviparous lizard|Common Lizard]] is widespread although not commonly seen.<ref>[http://www.islaynaturalhistory.org/mammchklst.htm "Mammals, Reptiles and Amphibians"]. Islay Natural History Trust.  Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref> The island supports a significant population of the [[Marsh Fritillary]] along with numerous other moths and butterflies.<ref>[http://www.islaynaturalhistory.org/speciesfiles/recordfiles/Mothsandbutterflies/Current/index.html "Islay Wildlife Records <U+2013> Moths and Butterflies Index"]. Islay Natural History Trust.  Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref> The mild climate supports a diversity of flora, typical of the [[Inner Hebrides#Wildlife|Inner Hebrides]].<ref>[http://www.islaynaturalhistory.org/speciesfiles/recordfiles/Floweringplants/Current/index.html "Islay Wildlife Records <U+2013> Flowering plants Index"]. Islay Natural History Trust.  Retrieved 23 April 2012.</ref>

==Notable natives==
[[File:Port Ellen, Islay.jpg|thumb|[[Port Ellen]]]]
* [[John Francis Campbell]], authority on Celtic folklore and joint inventor of the [[Campbell<U+2013>Stokes recorder]]. The son of Daniel Campbell of Shawfield, his father's bankruptcy prevented him inheriting the Islay estate. There is a monument commemorating him at Bridgend.<ref>Haswell-Smith (2004) p. 43</ref>
* [[Glenn Campbell (broadcaster)|Glenn Campbell]], Scottish political reporter for the BBC, was brought up on Islay and attended Islay High School.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/politics_show/2813111.stm| title=Meet presenter Glenn Campbell| accessdate=23 Jan 2008| work=BBC News | date=2 Mar 2003}}</ref>
* [[Alistair Carmichael]], the Liberal Democrat Deputy Chief Whip, was born on Islay to hill-farming parents. He has represented [[Orkney and Shetland (UK Parliament constituency)|Orkney and Shetland]] at [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Westminster]] since 2001.<ref>[http://www.scotlibdems.org.uk/people/alistair-carmichael "Alistair Carmichael"] Scottish Liberal Democrats. Retrieved 23 Mar 2012.</ref>
* The Islay-born Reverend [[Donald Caskie]] (1902<U+2013>1983) became known as the "Tartan Pimpernel" for his exploits in France during World War II.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/our-man-in-marseilles-1-590900 "Our man in Marseilles"]. (27 Dec 2001) Edinburgh. ''The Scotsman''. Retrieved 19 Sept 2012.</ref>
* [[John Crawfurd]] was born on Islay in 1783 and during a long career as a [[colonial administrator]] he became governor of [[Singapore]]. He also wrote a number of books including ''Journal of an Embassy from the Governor General of India to the Courts of Siam and Cochin China'' (1828).<ref>Turnbull, C. M. (2004) [http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/6/101006651/ "Crawfurd, John (1783<U+2013>1868), orientalist  and colonial administrator"]. ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''. Retrieved 19 Sept 2012.</ref>  
* [[Alexander McDougall|General Alexander McDougall]], a figure in the [[American Revolution]] and the first president of the [[Bank of New York]], was born in Kildalton in 1731.<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000415 "McDougall, Alexander, (1731<U+2013>1786)"]. United States Congress. Retrieved 23 Mar 2012.</ref>
* [[George Robertson, Baron Robertson of Port Ellen|George Robertson]], formerly secretary-general of NATO and British [[Defence Secretary]]. In 1999 he was made Lord Robertson of Port Ellen.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nato.int/cv/secgen/robert-e.htm | title = NATO Secretary General (1999<U+2013>2003) The Rt. Hon. Lord Robertson of Port Ellen | accessdate = 19 Sept 2012 | author = | date = 6 Jan 2004 | work = Who is who at NATO? | publisher = [[NATO]]}}</ref>
* [[William Stewart (scientist)|Sir William Stewart]] (born 1935) steered a course from Bowmore junior school to become the UK government<U+2019>s [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser|Chief Scientific Adviser]] in the late 1980s and early 1990s.<ref>[http://www.napier.ac.uk/alumni/news/HonGrads/Pages/SirWilliamStewart.aspx "Sir William Stewart Doctor of Science"]. Edinburgh Napier University. Retrieved 19 Sept 2012.</ref>

